p, and generosity toward other peoples. Through personal contacts and the media, musical diplomacy also created subtle musical, social, and political relationships on a global scale. Although born of state-sponsored tours often conceived as propaganda ventures, these relationships were in themselves great diplomatic achievements and constituted the essence of America’s soft power. Using archival documents and newly collected oral histories, Danielle Fosler-Lussier shows that musical diplomacy had vastly different meanings for its various participants, including government officials, musicians, concert promoters, and audiences. Through the stories of musicians from Louis Armstrong and Marian Anderson to orchestras and college choirs, Fosler-Lussier deftly explores the value and consequences of "musical diplomacy."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArts and diplomacyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMusic and globalizationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMusic in intercultural communicationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  a20th century composers.  a20th century music.  aaccessible music.  abela bartok.  abela viktor janos bartok.  acareer.  acold war tensions.  acold war.  acomparative musicology.  aethnomusicology.  afolk music.  ahermann scherchen.  ahungarian composer.  ainternational politics.  airon curtain.  amodernism.  amusic.  amusical legacy.  amusical style.  amusicians.  aperforming arts.  apianist.  apierre boulez.  apolitical action.  apolitical pressure.  apolitics.  aradio programs.  asocialist realism.  asocialist state.  atheodor adorno.  awestern composers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211